      <section id="what-is-aws">
        <h2>What is AWS?</h2>
        <p>Amazon Web Services (AWS) is a comprehensive cloud computing platform offered by Amazon. AWS provides a wide range of services, including compute, storage, databases, analytics, machine learning, security, and more, all delivered as a service over the internet.</p>
      </section>
      <section id="aws-features">
        <h2>AWS Features</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>Scalability and Elasticity</li>
          <li>Reliability and Availability</li>
          <li>Security and Compliance</li>
          <li>Flexibility and Agility</li>
          <li>Cost-Effective</li>
        </ul>
      </section>
      <section id="aws-benefits">
        <h2>AWS Benefits</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>Global Infrastructure</li>
          <li>Reduced Time to Market</li>
          <li>Pay as You Go Pricing</li>
          <li>Highly Scalable and Flexible</li>
          <li>Secure and Compliant</li>
        </ul>
      </section>
      <section id="getting-started">
        <h2>Getting Started with AWS</h2>
        <p>To get started with AWS, sign up for an AWS account and explore the various services offered by AWS. AWS provides extensive documentation and tutorials to help users get started and learn how to use AWS services effectively.</p>
        <p>Some popular AWS services to get started with include Amazon EC2, Amazon S3, Amazon RDS, and AWS Lambda.</p>
